<hr>
<i>Posted by Melyodas on 03-24-2004 04:09 PM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>I heard back from SOE about this proration deal, finally.<br />
<br />
Don't have the email with me to quote from, but basicly what they told me is once you buy time, the purchase is final, but you won't ever lose time you have bought if you go to another plan.<br />
<br />
In other words, if you get the $99 thing now, then upgrade to the All Access plan later with time left on the current plan, your leftover EQ-only time from the $99 deal gets shifted to the end of the upgraded plan.<br />
<br />
Unless you plan to buy EQ2, play it for a while, then cancel and go back to EQ only, this is pretty impractical and as such, basicly amounts to actually losing the time.  While technically you don't, in practice, you do.<br />
<br />
My view is that, basicly, when compared to regular monthly billing, the break even point for the $99 plan is roughly October.....You only save money with this if you play EQ only past October.....So if EQ2 comes out before October you actually lose money....To get the full savings, EQ2 can't come out before April '05.<br />
<br />
If EQ2 comes out in September (as listed on EBGames) I will laugh, because that basicly means SOE got people (who don't play PlanetSide) to pre-pay for the last 6 months of EQ before EQ2 with zero savings while thinking they were getting a great deal.  Factor in the upcoming release of WoW and other games that may pull people away from EQ during that time and it's really not a deal at all.<!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: postbit_signature -->
